Comment: 0,0:00:03.96,0:00:05.31,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}英文字幕
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.96,0:00:05.31,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Hello it's Scott Manley here.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.72,0:00:10.86,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Over the weekend Israel made a surprise launch of the Ofeq 16 satellite.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.23,0:00:16.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This was launched onboard a Shavit-2 rocket and was billed as an earth observation satellite.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.26,0:00:20.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Really it's a military reconnaissance satellite.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.33,0:00:24.11,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Israel have been launching satellites on their own for quite a while.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.11,0:00:26.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They actually started developing reconnaissance satellites.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.65,0:00:31.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}More or less after the 1973 Yom Kippur War.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.08,0:00:37.80,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Because US assets were not able to deliver the intelligence they wanted quickly enough for various reasons
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.80,0:00:43.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so they developed their own launch system and they've been running this since but 1988
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.59,0:00:47.39,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So this is the ninth successful launch of an Ofeq satellite.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.39,0:00:52.71,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The last Ofeq satellite launched was or Ofeq 11 and that was launched in 2016
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.14,0:00:56.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}We don't actually know what happened to Ofeq 12 to 15.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.44,0:01:02.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I suspect they might be part of some canceled design or they might be getting launched later.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.76,0:01:04.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I'm not really sure
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.40,0:01:09.81,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Regardless. To satellite watchers that Ofeq satellites are kind of fascinating oddballs.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.81,0:01:15.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So like all things launched from Israel, they're launched by the Shavit rocket
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.43,0:01:17.90,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and they're launched into a retrograde orbit
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.90,0:01:19.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}they're going the wrong direction around the earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.57,0:01:24.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So all of the spacecraft launched by Israel have an orbit.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.09,0:01:27.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}There's roughly a 142 degrees of inclination
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.07,0:01:32.80,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which means they're sort of going west or east to west rather than west to east.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.12,0:01:36.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And yeah this is highly unusual in space launch
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.03,0:01:41.17,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}because of course going west to east you pick up the velocity of the earth
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.63,0:01:45.21,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but they need to do this because it's a requirement
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.21,0:01:50.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}that they don't drop spent rocket stages on any of their neighbors to the east
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.70,0:01:52.95,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They have Jordan. They have Saudi Arabia.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.39,0:01:59.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Various other nations to the east which are which might have not be happy if they drop something on them.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.23,0:02:06.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Alternatively, Israel may not want these nations to be examining the spent rocket hardware
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.59,0:02:11.67,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and that is another reason why they choose to launch over the Mediterranean.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.67,0:02:18.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So all the launches occur from Palmachim Airbase and then they head west out over the Mediterranean Sea
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.95,0:02:25.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and it's believed if the rocket were able to launch eastwards they would more than double their payload capacity
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.44,0:02:29.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but even going west they're actually very careful with their launch trajectories.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.08,0:02:33.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The kind of tried to stay over the Mediterranean as much as possible
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.56,0:02:37.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}practically aiming to thread the needle over the Straits of Gibraltar
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.00,0:02:42.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}that means they're carefully sliding between Europe and Africa
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.93,0:02:47.68,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so the Shavit rockets are built by the Israel Aerospace Industries
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.69,0:02:50.81,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and the current version of this is the Shavit 2
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.24,0:02:56.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and it's an evolution obviously of the original Shavit which launched back in 1988.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.84,0:02:59.85,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The design is an all solid rocket motor design.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.93,0:03:02.72,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}It uses three solid rocket stages.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.43,0:03:06.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The first two stages are practically identical.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.00,0:03:10.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They're the same mass, the same diameter in the same length.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.40,0:03:14.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But the second stage has a larger vacuum optimized nozzle.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.79,0:03:23.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So on the original Shavit the stages are 1.3 meters in diameter and 6.4 meters long and the mass is about 10 tons.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.51,0:03:25.88,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Slightly different because of the different nozzle sizes.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.66,0:03:32.67,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Both these stages burn for 52 seconds and the first stage will generate 46 tons of thrust.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.67,0:03:38.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}In the second thrust the second stage gets 48 tons of thrust thanks to that larger nozzle.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.91,0:03:42.20,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Now the third stage is much smaller.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.20,0:03:45.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}It's only 2.6 meters long and it's a big 2.6 tons.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.15,0:03:49.61,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}It'll generate 6.2 tons of thrust for 90 seconds.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.18,0:03:55.59,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Unlike the previous stages this doesn't have any steering capability or any thrust vectoring.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.59,0:03:56.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}It's spin stabilized.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.91,0:04:04.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So during the launch the first two stages fire and accelerate the rocket up onto a ballistic trajectory.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.50,0:04:07.90,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And they'll typically burn out at around 100 kilometers
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.98,0:04:13.19,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}when the vehicle will continue upwards to reach about 250 kilometers.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.54,0:04:19.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}During the cruise up to that apogee altitude, there is an equipment section on the top,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.04,0:04:23.67,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}there which will it basically encompasses the second stage
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.68,0:04:25.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and you can actually see this in the video that was released.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.25,0:04:32.80,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}it points this in the correct orientation and then spins up the upper-stage before a letting go.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.09,0:04:39.50,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Then when that upper stage finally fires its spin stabilized and the spacecraft is put into the correct orbit.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.28,0:04:46.83,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So the Shavit 1 or the Shavit's design was used to launch the first two satellites Ofeq 1 and 2.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.95,0:04:53.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Those had masses of about 160 kilograms and then they introduced an upgrade, the Shavit 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.06,0:04:58.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They just stretched that first stage to 7.5 meters long.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.53,0:04:59.84,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}That's an extra meter long.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.41,0:05:05.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They also made it wider by five centimeters one point three five meters in total.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.77,0:05:11.27,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So that raised the total mass to 14 tons and the thrust was up to 62 tons.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.73,0:05:18.54,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And this was used for four launches Ofeq three through six from 1995 to 2004.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.03,0:05:21.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But two of these launches were unsuccessful.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.51,0:05:24.71,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Those satellites were significantly heavier.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.92,0:05:32.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But you know the final version that flew over the weekend is the Shavit 2 that debuted in 2007.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.66,0:05:36.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And all they did was they took that stretched first stage
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.68,0:05:40.28,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and they made the second stage use that stretched model as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.29,0:05:44.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So you can tell the difference or which design of Shavit rocket is
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.30,0:05:49.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}using by looking for where the ridge is where the rocket changes diameter.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.52,0:05:56.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So yeah the Shavit 2 has been able to launch 260 kilogram spacecraft by the sound of things.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.37,0:05:59.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And yeah that's what they're flying these days.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.86,0:06:07.39,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Now the design of the Shavit rocket actually goes back to Israel's ICBM project called Jericho.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.91,0:06:14.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}That began in the 1960s and the primary development was originally carried out by Dassault Aviation in France.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.82,0:06:23.27,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The first and second stages of the Shavit are literally taken directly from the Jericho 2 missile.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.27,0:06:27.21,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}In fact most of what we know about the performance of the Jericho missiles
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.74,0:06:30.98,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}are derived from the performance of the Shavit launch vehicle.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.91,0:06:35.27,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The design incidentally was also licensed to South Africa
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.27,0:06:39.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and they produced a series of missiles and rockets called the RSA series.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.01,0:06:41.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}These were ballistic missiles.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.44,0:06:44.25,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They also worked on building a launch vehicle
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.43,0:06:50.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and they actually had three suborbital launches which were carried out in 1989 and 1990.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.80,0:06:55.26,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But before they reached orbit the program was cancelled in 1994.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.16,0:07:00.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}There was one other spin-off where there was an attempt to commercialize the project.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.16,0:07:07.12,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}That was a partnership between IAI and Astrium and that began in 2001.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.16,0:07:09.84,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They incorporated, set it up, started advertising it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.44,0:07:14.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Curiously because of US government rules on launch vehicles.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.34,0:07:21.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They ended up deciding to essentially build a copy of Shavit in the US using US hardware.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.46,0:07:27.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So one design had a file called Castor 120 motor as the first and second stages.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.41,0:07:31.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And then the third stage would be a file called Star 48.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.84,0:07:38.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And uh actually the commercial versions all added this a monopropellant hydrazine engine on the top
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.08,0:07:43.73,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so they could what that would actually help with their orbit trim and orbit insertion accuracy.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.73,0:07:44.72,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I'm pretty sure.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.23,0:07:51.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But yeah this thing was apparently incorporated in 2001 and I haven't seen any updates on it
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.34,0:07:54.45,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so I'm gonna presume that that whole project is dead.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.34,0:07:59.80,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Also something keeps coming back is the idea of air launching the Shavit
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.80,0:08:04.88,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and you know air launch has limited gains we've also obviously mentioned this before
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.93,0:08:08.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but the Shavit actually stands to gain a lot if it was air launched.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.48,0:08:15.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Because as we points to it normally launches westwards over the Mediterranean
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.43,0:08:21.20,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but if you could put it on say a Boeing 747 or Hercules
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.84,0:08:27.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}if they could be carried out of Israel down through the Red Sea and over into the Indian Ocean
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.48,0:08:32.64,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and then they could launch eastwards and they could take advantage of the rotation of the earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.67,0:08:37.95,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They could get a significant boost front from that and it would get a boost from being air launched.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.58,0:08:43.45,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So that actually makes a lot more sense but I'm not sure that's gonna happen either.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.41,0:08:49.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So summing up the Shafiq is a curious launch vehicle for many reasons.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.22,0:08:52.99,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Partly the history, partly the reasons behind it working.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.70,0:08:58.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And you know honestly it doesn't actually make very much sense as a launch vehicle for anyone
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.51,0:09:03.13,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}except the Israeli military whose secrecy is very important to their payloads
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.46,0:09:07.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and at that point it makes just enough sense to exist.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.61,0:09:11.24,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But for heavier payloads that don't need that level of secrecy,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.27,0:09:18.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}they can actually buy launch services from other providers which have well the better situated launch sites.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.80,0:09:21.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I'm Scott Manley. Fly safe.
